00:00:23.060 --> 00:00:24.360
&gt;&gt; Eugene Flanagan: Hello.

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:27.390
I'm Eugene Flanagan,
Director of National Programs

00:00:27.390 --> 00:00:29.090
at The Library of Congress.

00:00:29.090 --> 00:00:31.470
And it's my pleasure to
welcome you here this afternoon

00:00:31.470 --> 00:00:35.520
to Spotlight on Native Writers.

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:37.930
The event is sponsored
by The Library's Poetry

00:00:37.930 --> 00:00:41.080
and Literature Center, home to
among other programs The Library

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:43.910
of Congress Prize for
American Fiction presented

00:00:43.910 --> 00:00:46.610
in 2010 to Louise Erdrich.

00:00:46.610 --> 00:00:49.980
Last fall Erdrich participated
in a terrific session

00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:52.670
of the National Book
Festival, and we are excited

00:00:52.670 --> 00:00:55.960
to have today's event occurring in
conjunction with Erdrich's return

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:59.890
to the Capitol for the debut of
her new novel, and you'll hear more

00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:04.350
about that later from Rob
Caspar, the Head of the Center.

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:08.130
Spotlight on Native
Writers gives The Library

00:01:08.130 --> 00:01:10.570
of Congress an opportunity
to feature a few

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:14.900
of the many essential Native
literary voices active today.

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:18.800
And Erdrich has prefaced today's
event with the observation that,

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:22.570
and I quote, bringing our
contemporary Native stories to life

00:01:22.570 --> 00:01:26.550
in one of our country's
greatest institutions is a worthy

00:01:26.550 --> 00:01:29.100
and delightful enterprise.

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:35.630 position:56%
Helping us today in that enterprise,
that delightful enterprise, right,

00:01:35.630 --> 00:01:38.810
are our four guests,
three on the stage now.

00:01:38.810 --> 00:01:42.210
Eric Gansworth is an artist and
author of 10 novels and a play.

00:01:42.210 --> 00:01:44.860
In the fall Eric will be
NEH Visiting Professor

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:47.940
of Native American Studies
at Colgate University.

00:01:47.940 --> 00:01:51.340
His next novel is Give
Me Some Truth.

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:54.200
Linda LeGarde Grover is a
writer and poet and the winner

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:56.300
of the Flannery O'Connor Award.

00:01:56.300 --> 00:01:58.870
Linda is a Professor of American
Indian Studies at the University

00:01:58.870 --> 00:02:02.610
of Minnesota, Duluth, and her next
poetry collection is titled The

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:04.720
Sky Watched.

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:08.180
Stephen Graham Jones is
the author of 16 novels

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:10.980
and six short story collections.

00:02:10.980 --> 00:02:14.470
Stephen teaches in the FMA programs
of the University of Colorado

00:02:14.470 --> 00:02:18.020
at Boulder and the University of
California, Riverside-Palm Desert,

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:20.490
and his current novel is Mongrels.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:22.950
Following readings by Eric,

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:26.490
Linda and Stephen we will have a
moderated discussion led by poet

00:02:26.490 --> 00:02:28.210
and scholar, Deborah Miranda.

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:31.620
Deborah is the John Lucian Smith
[Assumed Spelling] Junior Professor

00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:34.640
of English at Washington and
Lee University and author

00:02:34.640 --> 00:02:36.510
of three books of poetry.

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:39.840
Her next book is collection
of essays, The Hidden Stories

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:42.860
of Isabelle Meadows and Other
California Indian Lucini

00:02:42.860 --> 00:02:44.160
[Assumed Spelling].

