&gt;&gt; Eric Gansworth: I was
kind of the reader kid,

00:54:26.990 --> 00:54:29.660
I mean even though I was not
a particularly huge reader,

00:54:29.660 --> 00:54:32.590
like everybody in my family
hated reading, so that I liked it

00:54:32.590 --> 00:54:37.740
at all was kind of an anomaly.

00:54:37.740 --> 00:54:41.530
And I discovered, the Cliff notes
for my cousins, they don't want

00:54:41.530 --> 00:54:45.380
to read their books, they knew
I read books so they asked me

00:54:45.380 --> 00:54:49.100
to read their books and tell them
what it was they were supposed

00:54:49.100 --> 00:54:51.020
to have read for class.

00:54:51.020 --> 00:54:57.660
And I discovered The Red Pony and
To Kill a Mockingbird very early,

00:54:57.660 --> 00:55:00.430
and book now called The Pig Man.

00:55:00.430 --> 00:55:05.840
And I just found that I was being
moved by them, that I really wanted

00:55:05.840 --> 00:55:09.630
to meet these characters and it was
kind of that love of Stephen King

00:55:09.630 --> 00:55:14.790
after discovering that you could do
something beyond the novelization.

00:55:14.790 --> 00:55:18.580
And the tremendous luxury of right
as I was beginning to be serious

00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:21.330
about writing, Love
Medicine came out,

00:55:21.330 --> 00:55:26.430
so I was 19 when Love Medicine
came out and I thought, oh,

00:55:26.430 --> 00:55:28.610
well, this is what you can do.

00:55:28.610 --> 00:55:33.000
And so Louise Erdrich's, her first
novel was a really defining moment

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:35.770
for me as a writer.

00:55:35.770 --> 00:55:37.070
&gt;&gt; Stephen Graham Jones:
You know, I started out,

00:55:37.070 --> 00:55:39.930
by the time I was 12 I had read
all of Louis L'amour's novels.

00:55:39.930 --> 00:55:42.290
Up until that time
there were 95 of them,

00:55:42.290 --> 00:55:43.930
and I thought they were
true, they were gospel.

00:55:43.930 --> 00:55:47.760
They're not exactly best friends
of the Indian or anything,

00:55:47.760 --> 00:55:50.060
but I loved them, you
know, I loved them.

00:55:50.060 --> 00:55:52.290
And I read novelizations,
too, the horror movies.

00:55:52.290 --> 00:55:54.740
I remember seeing inside Jason
Borghese's [Assumed Spelling] head

00:55:54.740 --> 00:55:56.120
was so cool and everything.

00:55:56.120 --> 00:55:59.760
But then, yes, I graduated -
I don't know if I graduated,

00:55:59.760 --> 00:56:03.380
graduated suggests a hierarchy - I
moved like laterally into Pynchon,

00:56:03.380 --> 00:56:07.660
Thomas Pynchon, and then
Thomas Pynchon was a gateway

00:56:07.660 --> 00:56:09.350
to Jerald Bezener [Assumed
Spelling].

00:56:09.350 --> 00:56:13.770
And then from tracking down Jerald
Bezener, everybody around him,

00:56:13.770 --> 00:56:16.380
I did - this sounds corny that
I would say Love Medicine, too,

00:56:16.380 --> 00:56:19.870
but Love Medicine really was a
transformative work for a lot

00:56:19.870 --> 00:56:21.880
of us, I suspect, you know?

00:56:21.880 --> 00:56:23.180
It did hit me hard.

00:56:23.180 --> 00:56:25.220
I've read that book a lot
of times trying to figure

00:56:25.220 --> 00:56:29.830
out its peculiar magic, and I don't
think I've figured it out yet.

00:56:29.830 --> 00:56:34.970
And, yes, Stephen King,
too, definitely [inaudible]

00:56:34.970 --> 00:56:36.320
and just comic books, too.

00:56:36.320 --> 00:56:38.080
I grew up on comic books, you know?

00:56:38.080 --> 00:56:40.060
I still read comic
books all the time.

00:56:40.060 --> 00:56:42.030
If I could draw I wouldn't
have any novels published

00:56:42.030 --> 00:56:46.990
because I'd be trying to
do comic books, you know?

00:56:46.990 --> 00:56:48.290
&gt;&gt; Linda LeGarde Grover:

00:56:48.290 --> 00:56:52.980
My inspiration I guess would be
the stories that I listened to

00:56:52.980 --> 00:56:57.420
and eavesdropped on when I
was a child because I was one

00:56:57.420 --> 00:57:02.250
of those kids who read a lot but
was also directed to get my nose

00:57:02.250 --> 00:57:04.090
out of the book and
go outside and play.

00:57:04.090 --> 00:57:06.800
And then I would hang
around and eavesdrop,

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:10.240
and so probably annoyed
the adults very much.

00:57:10.240 --> 00:57:13.590
But that became like
reading a book for me,

00:57:13.590 --> 00:57:15.990
and I've always loved reading.

00:57:15.990 --> 00:57:21.330
I mean I read everything
I saw when I was a child.

00:57:21.330 --> 00:57:25.330
My uncle was - one of my uncles was
a janitor in our school district

00:57:25.330 --> 00:57:29.350
and he actually was supposed to be
disposing of a bunch of old books,

00:57:29.350 --> 00:57:32.880
and a ton of them were about
Russia during the Czar time,

00:57:32.880 --> 00:57:34.360
novels, history books.

00:57:34.360 --> 00:57:36.990
And he was supposed to toss them
out or incinerate them or whatever,

00:57:36.990 --> 00:57:38.650 position:56%
and he brought them up to our house.

00:57:38.650 --> 00:57:42.190
And so when I was a kid I had
a great time reading those.

00:57:42.190 --> 00:57:45.480
He brought me a big box of Reader's
Digests from the '40s and '50s

00:57:45.480 --> 00:57:47.410
and I loved reading those, too.

00:57:47.410 --> 00:57:50.050
I love Agatha Christie.

00:57:50.050 --> 00:57:55.620
I love Louise Erdrich's stuff
and for me the Erdrich book

00:57:55.620 --> 00:57:59.050
for me was Tracks when it came out

00:57:59.050 --> 00:58:00.610
and Fleur Pillager
[Assumed Spelling].

00:58:00.610 --> 00:58:05.390
So I loved to listen and
to read, and eventually

00:58:05.390 --> 00:58:07.800
after awhile I started
to write them I guess.

00:58:10.010 --> 00:58:11.310
&gt;&gt; Stephen Graham Jones: You
know, that compulsion to read,

00:58:11.310 --> 00:58:12.770
I had that too when I was a kid.

00:58:12.770 --> 00:58:15.980
I'd run out of Reader's Digests
so I'd go to my grandma's kitchen

00:58:15.980 --> 00:58:18.750 position:56%
